Probably the best reference for the `iter`/`iter_mut`/`into_iter` names
is [this API guideline entry][api].

As to `iter`/`iter_mut` not having traits: part of the reason that this
isn’t necessary is precisely that `Vec<T>`, `&Vec<T>`, and `&mut Vec<T>`
implement `IntoIter` for items `T`, `&T`, and `&mut T`, respectively, so
if you want to be generic over a container with “something like `iter`”
you can just take `IntoIterator<Item = &T>` and pass `&my_vec`.

The trait also turns out to not be as ergonomic as you might like. Look
at the signature of, say, [`HashSet::iter`]:

```rust
pub fn iter<'a>(&'a self) -> hash_set::Iter<'a, T>;
```

The returned iterator has a lifetime tied to the reference to the set
itself, as it must, since it returns references that point _into_ the
hash set. So your trait would be like:

```rust
trait Iterable<'a> {
    type Item: 'a;
    type Iter: Iterator<Item = Self::Item> + 'a;
    
    fn iter(&'a self) -> Self::Iter;
}
```

…and its implementers like:

```rust
use std::collections::hash_set::{self, HashSet};

impl<'a, K: 'a> Iterable<'a> for HashSet<K> {
    type Item = &'a K;
    type Iter = hash_set::Iter<'a, K>;
    
    fn iter(&'a self) -> Self::Iter {
        self.iter()
    }
}
```

