We will need to replace the line above with something like;
```
pytest -vv -n N --reruns M --dist loadscope tests/end_to_end --json-report --json-report-file=TEST_REPORT-end-to-end.json
```
`N` is number of threads running in parallel, and `M` will be number of retries that we need to do for each test case in case they fail. From their documentation (https://pytest-xdist.readthedocs.io/en/stable/distribution.html);
> `--dist loadscope`: Tests are grouped by module for test functions and by class for test methods. Groups are distributed to available workers as whole units. This guarantees that all tests in a group run in the same process. This can be useful if you have expensive module-level or class-level fixtures. Grouping by class takes priority over grouping by module.

What do you think about having separate constructors for Vec<u8> and [u8; LEN] strings? In the case of the Vec I think it might be nice to have the constructor be infallible. It's a variable length string so we can just add a null byte. And for the fixed strings we could still return an error (in addition to now checking the length of the string (at compile time)). Or we could make everything infallible by padding short strings + setting the last byte to 0  

```rust
impl SbpString<Vec<u8>, NullTerminated> {
    pub fn null_terminated(data: impl Into<Vec<u8>>) -> Self {
        let mut data = data.into();
        if data.last().map_or(true, |n| n != &0) {
            data.push(0);
        }
        Self::new(data)
    }
}

impl<const LEN: usize> SbpString<[u8; LEN], NullTerminated> {
    // accepting an array instead of AsRef<[u8]> checks the length at compile time
    pub fn null_terminated(data: [u8; LEN]) -> Result<Self, NullTerminatedError> {
        match data.last() {
            Some(l) if l == &0 => Ok(Self::new(data)),
            _ => Err(NullTerminatedError),
        }
    }
}
// or if we want an infallible api
impl<const LEN: usize> SbpString<[u8; LEN], NullTerminated> {
    pub fn null_terminated(data: impl AsRef<[u8]>) -> Self {
        let mut s: [u8; LEN] = [0; LEN];
        s.copy_from_slice(data.as_ref());
        s[LEN - 1] = 0;
        Self::new(s)
    }
}
```

